{
	"nodes":[
		{"id":"1aeb0dd9586982de","type":"text","text":"# `/var/log` contains all the logs files\nNote : `System log daemon` is responsible for generating log files and also decides which types of file is generated and where it generated. Also which type of logs comes under which type of file. The logs are handled by `syslog`\n\n* For problem diagnosis we look inside `/var/log/messages`\n\n1. `cd /var/log`\n2. `ls -l /var/log`\n\n***\n\n# Logs files\n\n* `/var/log/messages` --> contains global messages, including the message that are logged during startup. There are several things thar are logged in `/var/log/messages` including `mail`, `cron`, `daemon`, `kern`, `auth` etc.\n***\n* `/var/log/dmesg` --> Contains kernel ring buffer information. When the system boots up, it print number of messages on the screen that displays information about the hardware devices that the kernel detects during boot process. These messages are available in kernel ring buffer and whenever the new messages comes the old messages gets overwritten. You can also view the content of the file using the `dmesg command`\n\n1. run `dmesg`\n","x":-660,"y":-280,"width":920,"height":740,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"78310efa5719e81e","type":"text","text":"# Logs files\n\n*  `/var/log/auth.log` --> Contains system authorization information, including user login and authentication mechanism that were used.\n\n***\n* `/var/log/boot.log` --> Contains information that are logged when the system boots\n\n***\n* `/var/log/daemon.log` --> Contains information logged by the various background daemon that runs on the system\n\n***\n* `/var/log/dpkg.log` --> Contains information that are logged when a package is installed or removed using `dpkg` command\n\n***\n* `/var/log/kern.log` --> Contains information logged by the kernel. Helpful for you to troubleshoot a custom-built kernel\n\n***\n* `/var/log/lastlog` --> Display the recent login information for all the users. This is not an ascii file. You should use `lastlog` command to view the content of the file.\n\n1. run `lastlog` ","x":280,"y":-280,"width":920,"height":760,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"84994a7180bd8ae2","type":"text","text":"# Logs files\n\n*  `/var/log/maillog` or `/var/log/mail.log` --> Contains the log information from the mail server that is running on the system. For example, send mail logs information about all the sent items to the file\n\n***\n* `/var/log/user.log` --> Contains information about all user level logs\n\n***\n* `/var/log/Xorg.x.log` --> Log message from the `X`. Related to `GUI`\n\n***\n* `/var/log/alternatives.log` --> Information by the update-alternatives are logged into this log file. On Ubuntu, update-alternatives maintains symbolic determining default commands\n***\n* `/var/log/btmp` --> This file contains information about failed login attempts. Use the last command to view the `btmp` file. For example, \n\n1. `last -f /var/log/btmp | more` or\n2. run `lastb`\n\n***\n* `/var/log/cups` --> All printer and printing related log messages\n","x":-660,"y":480,"width":920,"height":740,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"3e9463cc241fdeca","type":"text","text":"# Logs files\n\n*  `/var/log/httpd` or `/var/log/apache2` --> Contains the `apache` web server `access_log` and `error_log`\n\n***\n* `/var/log/lighttpd` --> Contains light `HTTPD` `acces_log` and `error_log`\n\n***\n* `/var/log/cron` --> Whenever `cron daemon` or `anacron` starts a `cton job`, it logs the information about the `cron job` in this file\n \n***\n* `/var/log/conman` --> Log files for `ConMan client`. conman connects remote consoles that are managed by command daemon.\n\n***\n* `/var/log/mail` --> This subdirectory contains additional logs from your mail server. For example, `sendmail` stores the collected mail statistics in `/var/log/mail/statistics` file\n\n***\n* `/var/log/prelink` -->`prelink` program modifies shared libraries and linked binaries to speed up the startup process. `/var/log/prelink/prelink.log` contains the information about the `.so` file that was modified by the `prelink`\n","x":-660,"y":1240,"width":920,"height":740,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"4bc8a880c6900df4","type":"text","text":"* `cat /etc/redhat-release`\n* `cat /etc/os-release`\n\nWill show operating system name","x":-321,"y":-520,"width":321,"height":148,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"0c3cff2b8fa2be5f","type":"text","text":"# System Logging & Logs Management in Linux","x":120,"y":-360,"width":680,"height":60,"color":"3"},
		{"id":"023158a72c2575f8","type":"text","text":"# Logs files\n\n*  `/var/log/audit` --> Contains logs information stored by the `Linux` audit `daemon (auditd)`\n\n***\n* `/var/log/setroubleshoot` --> `SELinux` uses `setroubleshootd` (SE Trouble Shoot Daemon) to notify about issues in security context files, and logs those information in this log file.\n\n***\n* `/var/log/samba` --> Contains log information stored by `samba`, Which is used to connect Windows to Linux\n \n***\n* `/var/log/sa` --> Contains the daily `sar files` that are collected by the `sysstat package`\n\n***\n* `/var/log/sssd` --> Use by system security services daemon that manage access to remote directories and authentication mechanisms.\n\n***\n\n","x":280,"y":1360,"width":920,"height":740,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"36803c485fa600ac","type":"text","text":"# Logs files\n\n*  `/var/log/anaconda.log` --> When you install Linux, all installation related messages are stored in this file\n\n***\n* `/var/log/yum.log` --> Contains information that are logged when a package is installed using yum\n\n***\n* `/var/log/cron` --> Whenever `cron daemon` or `anacron` starts a `cton job`, it logs the information about the `cron job` in this file\n \n***\n* `/var/log/wtmp` or `/var/run/utmp` --> Contains login records. Using `wtmp` you can find out who is logged into the system. `who` command this file to display the information\n\n1. `last` enter. This command internally run the `/var/log/wtmp` file\n2. `who` enter. This command internally run `/var/log/utmp` file \n\n***\n* `/var/log/secure` --> Contains information related to authentication and authorization privileges. For example, `sshd` logs all the messages here, including unsuccessful login\n\nThis file list all unsuccessful login using `su or ssh` command\n\n***\n* `/var/log/faillog` --> Contains user failed login attempts. Use `faillog command` to display the content of this file\n","x":280,"y":520,"width":920,"height":780,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"39dfc242ff16c350","type":"text","text":"The System log daemon/service and it's configuration file differs depending on the version of Linux used i.e.\n\n```\nRHEL 5: syslogd - /etc/syslog.conf\nRHEL 6: rsyslogd - /etc/rsyslog.conf\n\nrsyslogd is the service which manages all log files\n```\n\n```\n1. systemctl status rsyslog.service\n**** If it is running then it will generate log in /etc/var/log and if it is not running then it won't generate the log files ****\n\n2. man rsyslogd\n**** Opens the manual ****\n\n3. man rsyslog.conf\n**** Opens manual of conf file ****\n```\n\nIMPORTANT\n\n```\n1. cat /etc/rsyslog.conf\n   \n** This file contain selector and action meaning which type of log is for which file this config file decide **\n```","x":1240,"y":-280,"width":1020,"height":640,"color":"3"},
